rComments: Loved this class. Neu has an odd lecture style without powerpoints. His pace is fast but topics are interesting. Major amounts of reading but you get to learn about dreams! The exams are difficult but if you did all the readings, got a good grasp on the concepts, and attend lecture you will do good. get together and make a class study guide it help

Probably the best humanities Prof at UCSC. I had him for 3 classes. He is brilliant, clear,and doesn't but up with BS. His style is harsh to some,  but its sink or swim. Frankly he's just smart to put up with people who aren't following, or who just don't get it. He is expert in all the varied fields he teaches
He does not allow computers nor does he use one to aid in his lectures, which were boring overall. He did not clearly prepare you for the tests and puts random facts on his tests.

One hard midterm, one  cumulative final. He made this class way more difficult than it should have been by being (himself) a fast-talking, detail-oriented and boring lecturer. He did not engage me with the material at all. A mega-ton of reading got me tired of this class by week 2. If you have to take it, take it pass-no-pass and take good notes.

Overall boring. He doesn't use any visual aids so you have to just listen to him the entire time. He also jumps around I'm lecture which makes it hard to understand what he's talking about. Take good notes because he will put random facts he mentioned once on an exam!

Neu is knowledgable and interesting. He knows his stuff, but reads his extremely detailed and complicated lectures off a sheet, making it really fast and nearly impossible to take notes. It's an interesting class, and if you get a good TA, you'll do fine, I got an A. You'll have a paper due every week, and definitely go to midterm review sections.

This class is ridiculous. He makes you turn in your papers before class and then makes you read them to the other students as a way to move discussion. But if you get on his bad side, he will humiliate you in front of the class. He knows his material, but leaves no room for discussion. Hes pompous and downright rude.  Cool shirts though.

This class was pretty difficult. The amnt of reading was pretty insane. However, despite the workload, Ive learned a lot from this class.If you are interested in the field of legal studies I would HIGHLY recommend taking phil146. So much crucial informations. Just be sure to keep up with the reading or else you WILL fail.

Neu is a brilliant and qualified professor, the lectures are FULL of information, and he makes them interesting almost every time. I recommend this class, HOWEVER the amount of reading is somewhat ludicrous and some of it is horrifically dry. He doesn't seem to really want/expect his students to do well.

Neu is an interesting professor, the class was definitely interesting just based on the material. There was alot of reading to keep up on, and tests were mult.choice & essay format based on readings and his lectures. He is really enthusiastic about the material. Sections are voluntary

This class was really interesting, but very demanding. The way it was set up was not benefitcial, only midterm and final, midterm being worth 1/3 and final 2/3 of the final grade. Tests were difficult, would recomend this class only if you attend every lecture and do the 50-100 pg readings that are due each class. Section would also help alot.

this class is cross-listed as both psych and phil, it turns out that it should be listed only under phil, because it is definitely not psych.  it's really just a phil class that happens to deal with freud.  if you love psych, you won't love this class.

Horrible class. Waste of time. Makes you show up to lecture through quizzes then reiterates the readings  making lecture useless. I got A's on the midterm and final and got a B+ in the class because of the quizzes. I couldn't stand sitting through the lectures. IT is a fairly easy class with concepts not difficult at all to grasp.

This man has the coolest collection of shirts I've ever seen (watch out for the green courduroy one). He's really intelligent and interesting to listen to, although don't get on his bad side because he will probably humiliate you in front of the entire class.

interesting class and concepts.  Neu is good at presenting materials but definately reads straight from his paper.  Quizzes almost every class.  Some difficult readings.  Tests are fair and straightforward.  Tends to come off rude when answering questions from students in class!

I had Neu for intro to phil and law and he's a great teacher. Tests are long and based almost entirely on lecture. Lecture, likewise, is based almost entirely on reading. Both classes are 100% straightorward. I reccomend him for law, as this seems to really be his passion.
No Comments
It was really hard to pay attention after the break, but i never wanted to miss any of his lectures. It was always interesting and he really knows his stuff. I would recommend this class.
Snooooooooooooze. And I'm a philosophy major!
No Comments

I can see how he might be a bit much for an intro course, but in Philosophy of Law there is no one better/more qualified.  The class was rather difficult, but he was exceptionally clear and was always open for a little debate.  The man is brilliant.  Quizzes almost every day, so attendance is a must - but I never wanted to miss his class anyway.

They let a phil proff teach a psych course. Big mistake and worse seminar ever. Going to class was utterly pointless assignments were based on reading and were never ever talked about before they were due. He made us turn in stuff to his office every week 3 hours before class started. I hate him

He REALLY knows phil, is passionate, & made me excited to be a phil major.  Tests are based on lectures, so take good notes.  I barely did the readings, missed just one lecture, took pretty good notes, still learned a lot, and got a solid A in the class, even though my TA sucked. I def recommend him

I thought he lectured too slowly, and that lectures were read almost entirely off of his notes.  Reading were great and he knows the stuff well.  So while I found intro to phil boring, I also felt that I got a  great grasp on the basics of philosophy.

Great teacher!! You learn a lot in this class if you go to lectures.  He's passionate about phil, clear and concise with lectures.  Just make sure you have a good TA and you go to lectures.  Tests are almost entirely on them, but they're not too bad.  My TA sucked but I still got an A in the class.

His passion for philosophy clearly shows through his enthusiastic lecturing style. He does refer to detailed notes, but they keep his lectures organized. Hes an interesting & intelligent prof. Readings are tough to get through but interesting.

He reads right off his notes, aside from that his lectures are semi-interesting.  The reading is the best part of the class, which (this quarter) included Plato, Descartes, Kant, and Sartre.  One midterm and either a paper or final, and those were tough.

i'm a phil major taking intro, I hate his method of reading note cards as a lecture. he throws the info at you too fast to take notes and he doesn't really go into great detail with the reading. I got a C- on the midterm, hopefully I'll pass.
Very intellectual man, he knows his stuff and is a great lecturer.  Not too boring but his tests are difficult
